Inflation in Europe jumps over food
The accelerating inflation measured in the euro area is mainly due to the constant rise in food prices.
November price growth in 13 euro area countries was higher than expected, with annual inflation of 3.1 percent registered after 2.6 percent in October, Luxembourg's statistical office said.
The official forecast was only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the US, British and Canadian banks of issue, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the key interest rate, arguing that such a cut, together with rising raw material prices and falling unemployment, would lead to an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to bring the inflation rate below, but close to, two percent.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in an absurd situation: it has to discourage inflation so that it does not have to do anything about it later.
In Germany, November inflation of 3.3 percent is a fifteen-year record; In Spain, it rose from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
Inflation in the eurozone has plummeted due to soaring food and energy prices.
Penic forward prices rose by 88 percent, and soybean prices also reached their highest level since 1973.
Similarly, in 2007 it was necessary to pay significantly more for edible oil and dairy products.
The price of oil on world markets has risen by 52 percent this year, and last month it cost one barrel of black gold nearly $100.
According to the ECB, inflation will jump to 2.5 percent in 2008 from 2.1 percent this year, but will fall to 1.9 percent in 2009.
According to analysts, the level of 12-month inflation will remain at about 3 percent in the next 3-4 months, but its average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to cut interest rates twice during 2008.
