In many places, disinfectants are used
This year, more than a thousand cases of infection caused mainly by the inappropriate use of antibiotics were registered in hospitals.
Hygienic conditions of hospitals, overcrowding of beds, overloading of staff do not help to stop infections, according to the head physician of the National Epidemiological Center.
In many places, disinfectants are also being saved.
Recently, the trauma department of St. John's Hospital was diagnosed with MRSA infection.
Antibiotic-resistant bacteria were discovered in a mue who arrived at the hospital after a serious car accident.
The patient was isolated.
A similar infection occurred in the same place at the beginning of the year.
A patient injured in a car accident was rushed home, but had to return with an MRSA infection not long after, and because of a bacterium in his system, an important operation could not yet be performed.
By December 10 this year, 1,094 hospital infections caused by multidrug-resistant agents had been reported to the National Nesocomialis Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröcz, head physician of the National Epidemiological Center.
This means that so many infections caused by multidrug-resistant agents have been registered with certainty in hospitals, the rest are unknown.
Nearly two-thirds (683) of infections were caused by MRSA, or methicillin-oxacillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
A third of people carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) in their nose without causing disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g. throat inflammation, tonsillitis, equine infections, early infections) respond well to antibiotics and can be treated well.
If the antibiotic bag is given over- or inappropriately, it will develop into a bacterium that responds well to antibiotics, is very resistant to antibiotics and spreads rapidly in inadequate hospital conditions.
Especially in the case of temporary or permanent malfunctioning of the immune system in patients with a weakened organism, low body weight or in patients in years can cause serious hospital infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, sepsis.
According to the chief physician of St. John's Hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infection, such infections are part of daily practice in hospitals.
Infection is not to be confused with epidemics, MRSA is not only there, said Tibor Nyulasi, where the presence of the causative agent of the disease is not studied.
Resistant to antibiotics
We isolate these patients, the nursing staff treat them in rubber gloves and masks, and we have the necessary antibiotics to treat them, Tibor Nyulasi said.
Patients admitted to the hospital are first examined for the presence of MRSA in their body, but the bag of infection can not always be avoided.
Sampling is not fashionable
The vast majority of hospital infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but current conditions and conditions in home hospitals are not conducive to preventing the emergence and spread of multidrug-resistant agents, says Karolina Böröczová.
Since this infection is typically present in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should check on patients admitted and isolate MRSA carriers.
The collection of microbiological samples in Hungarian hospitals is not fashionable.
The fact that the National Health Insurance Fund does not finance these examinations also plays a role in this.
Most cases are detected when a patient suffers from a perceptible MRSA infection, said the head physician of the epidemiological center.
The European Union has strict recommendations for appropriate antibiotic treatment in the field of human medicine, and there are also domestic guidelines for the treatment of individual infections, medical records.
It is necessary to strive for antibiotic therapy to be targeted, i.e. microbiological tests should be carried out to prevent the development of drug resistance, but hospitals do not comply with this in all cases.
Sampling of microbiological samples is rarely in basic or outpatient treatment of patients, Karolina Böröczová said.
Saves on disinfectants
According to scientific evidence, MRSA spreads most frequently among patients through healthcare professionals.
Therefore, hand washing and the use of gloves and masks play a very important role, but there are serious shortcomings in hospitals.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection and touch, but in home hospitals it is not always possible to isolate infected patients.
On the contrary, the rooms are often overcrowded, the beds are often very close to each other, although from the epidemiological point of view, patients should be at least 1.5 meters apart.
As Karolina Böröczová noted, unfortunately we can also encounter the fact that hospitals that are in an unfavorable material situation, save on disinfectants, there are few caregivers and many patients, which increases the chance of infection.
According to Karolina Böröczová, where the necessary protective measures are observed, there are demonstrably fewer similar infections or the further spread of the causative agent of the disease can be stopped.
Government Program Against MRSA
Treating MRSA infection is a huge expense for health insurance companies, so it is being combated.
In England, for example, the government has drawn up a program to prevent MRSA, or to reduce its incidence.
The programme seems to be a success, with MRSA infections in England showing a downward trend, according to published data.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) makes the prevention of multi-persistent disease agents (MRSA) and hospital infections caused by these agents a priority.
The police captain, just caused the fatal accident, was not drunk
The official expert opinion in the case of the police captain of District XXII, who only caused a fatal accident, is complete.
It can be ruled out that the police captain of District XXII, who killed a pedestrian on Tuesday and who has since resigned from his post, was driving under the influence of alcohol or narcotics, Attila Morvai, spokesman for the Prosecutor General's Office of the capital, said on Friday after an expert opinion on the case was completed.
An expert opinion confirmed the result of the initial investigation, which concluded that the former police captain had not previously gotten behind the wheel, had not consumed any alcohol.
On Tuesday, the then director of the XXII Police Directorate in District XXII hit a fifty-five-year-old man who had stepped in front of him while crossing the road outside a marked crosswalk on Lajos Kossutha Street in District XXII.
(The latter fact, that the pedestrian crossed outside the zebra, is not a mitigating circumstance according to traffic rules; the turning car must still give way.)
After being taken to the hospital, the pedestrian died.
