An additional €400 million for infrastructure
An agreement on three loan lines worth a total of €400 million to support education, transport and environmental infrastructure as well as energy was signed on Friday in Budapest by Finance Minister János Veres and Marta Gajecka, Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB).
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) approved a framework of EUR 300 million for the Hungarian budget financing of transport and environment projects implemented with the Cohesion Fund support, whereas the parties had previously concluded a loan agreement for EUR 100 million, the contract now signed covers the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
A €150 million loan agreement is also used to finance education-related projects in the budget.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for Hungary for this purpose, the remaining EUR 150 million may be used at a later date, with the extension of the loan agreement.
In the area of innovation, the parties have signed a contract for €50 million, which the budget will mainly use for a research and development project of the University of Debrecen.
The 4th metro line was also discussed at the meeting.
The parties agreed that after Hungary agreed with the EU on the details of the financing of the metro, they would return to whether and how the original contract should be modified.
According to János Veres, this may happen in the first quarter of 2008.
The EIB has financed a total of 113 projects in Hungary with €8.4 billion since 1990.
The interest on EIB loans granted with a waiting period of eight years and without a commitment commission is linked to the EURIBOR rate.
