A giant strike is brewing
The League Trade Union Association and the National Union of Workers' Councils (MOSZ) will form a strike committee on Friday to coordinate Monday's indefinite strike.
A public protest meeting will be held on Saturday, and work will be halted on Monday on the day of the final vote on the health insurance law.
The action will certainly cause serious disruptions, as rail transport will almost completely stop and employees of the Budapest Transport Company (BKV) will also be on strike by 1 p.m.
On Friday afternoon, the League and the National Union of Workers' Councils will present details of Monday's jointly organized strike.
A strike committee will also be formed LIGA MOSZ, which will coordinate Monday's action.
On Saturday, a public protest meeting is held, and from Monday, unions joining the strike will stop work indefinitely unless an agreement is reached with the government.
This means that no date has been set for the end of the strike, which will begin on the day of the parliamentary vote on the Health Insurance Act.
Should Parliament ultimately fail to pass the health insurance law, the unions will withdraw the call for a strike.
If the legislation is passed, strike commissions will meet and decide on further action.
According to Monday's agenda of the session of Parliament, it is also possible that the law on health insurance will be voted on and in the late evening or night hours.
Due to the strike starting on Monday, traffic disruptions can be expected: work on the railway will be stopped indefinitely, part of Budapest's public transport may stop in the morning, and more than half of the Volán companies may stop.
At the same time, half of the lane will also be closed in many parts of the country.
Numerous trade unions and civil society organisations have joined the call for the strike, the list of which is constantly updated on the League website.
Some organizations announced a strike for an indefinite period, others declared a temporary halt to work.
By Thursday afternoon, the Hungarian State Railways (MÁV) and the Independent Union of Railway Employees (VDSZSZ) had not even been able to agree on sufficient services, while more and more people are travelling on the railway at the beginning of the Christmas holidays.
According to previous announcements, there will be a strike at BKV from the start of operations until 1 p.m., from 7 a.m. to 9 a.m. at Budapest Airport, a four-hour strike will be organized by the Energy Workers' Union LIGA, and the Teachers' Union has called for a 2- and 2-8-hour stoppage, respectively.
The Union of Hungarian Doctors will strike alternately across the country, while the Democratic Trade Union of Health and Social Workers (EDDSZ), part of the Cooperation Forum of Trade Unions (SZEF), is holding a two-hour strike.
The most important of the four demands formulated by the League Association is that the government revoke the proposal for health insurance reform and submit a new concept for public debate.
The second requirement is that the new method of counting pensions, effective from next year, be introduced gradually.
The third is to ensure that early retirement for the relevant sectors of employment can be included in the scheme before 2010.
The fourth reason for the action is that the Independent Union of Railway Employees (VDSZSZ), part of the League trade union, does not accept the offer of the Ministry of Economy and Transport concerning railway branches, and expects a different offer.
Political Capital: Hungarian Guard Increases Country Risk
According to Political Capital's Risk Analysis Division, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, founded with the support of Jobbik Magyarországért in August this year, have increased the political risk of Hungary and the region in several respects.
In connection with the activities of the Hungarian Guard, the greatest political risk is that by exacerbating the already existing ethnic tensions between the Roma and non-Roma population of Hungary, it may in a short time lead to violent ethnic clashes.
The main reason is that the political strategy of the Hungarian Guard is probably aimed at provoking such an action, the research institute adds.
As he writes, this can be explained by one of the greatest negligence of Hungarian political representatives: public representatives of public life left the public discussion of the Roma issue to representatives of radical and extremist political groups who could build a political strategy on the Roma-Hungarian conflict.
This exacerbates the problem, hinders normal dialogue, strengthens extremists and increases the likelihood of violent conflicts.
In addition, according to the research institute, the activities of the Hungarian Guard have largely damaged the image of Hungary abroad, especially in terms of faith in the stability of the country and its democratic maturity, due to the great attention of domestic and foreign media.
As part of the reorganization of Hungarian radical and far-right groups, which has received increasing publicity and vehemence since autumn 2006, several self-calling national militia associations have been created in Hungary since the summer of 2007.
The common feature of these groupings is that they define themselves as civic associations, while openly proclaiming the armed readiness of their members to perform defensive tasks (in the event of major disasters, attacks on the homeland, disruption of order), moreover, referring to the incompetence of the police, the army, or the state, he adds.
He goes on to note: this is done in a way that seeks to wrap up various political endeavors built on society's opposition to politics and parties in civilian clothing.
In the case of these groups, emphasizing civility and the form of the association does not only serve to avoid the legal pitfalls of judicial registration, but is also a political strategy.
According to the analysis, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are also a factor increasing the risk in terms of neighbourly relations.
In recent months, they have pointed to the Hungarian Guard in several neighboring states as a potential source of danger, and ultranationalist political leaders of some neighboring countries want to excuse their own anti-Hungarian policies by citing the formation of the Hungarian Guard.
This may affect the political stability of the region, he adds.
According to the research institute, the emergence of the Hungarian Guard in Central and Eastern Europe is not an isolated phenomenon, and political risks for the region as a whole have also increased.
The activities of the Hungarian Guard are similar to, for example, those of the Bulgarian National Guard, whose creation was announced in August 2007 by the far-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU).
The background to the formation of the Bulgarian Guard is the mass Roma riots that broke out in one of Sofia's neighborhoods (Krasna Polyana).
The BNU used this to establish the Guard, with the goal of the organization being the national militia.
Over the past 17 years, Gypsy terror has occurred in Bulgaria, but the state has remained inactive and indifferent.
He adds that the initiative has provoked a stormy discussion among the Bulgarian public.
The increased risk of ethnic clashes is signaled by the announcement by some Bulgarian Roma organizations that they will form their own guard as a sign of resistance.
