Holidays are not free
In Hungary, days off are precisely laid down by law, and it has become a general practice to move working days around holidays, which will be less common next year.
In the European Union and America, holidays are not uniform.
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between national and public holidays and non-working days.
Non-working days are usually associated with church holidays or important historical events.
We also celebrate the New Year: the last day of the old and the first day of the new year is a New Year's Day off so that people can relax after New Year's Eve.
During the year we have a total of eleven free holidays.
The national holiday is 15 March, celebrating the Revolution of 1848, and 23 October, the memorial day of the 1956 revolution.
On August 20 we celebrate the founding of the state, on May 1 we celebrate work, on November 1 and 2 we remember deceased relatives and friends.
In addition, the two-day holidays are Easter, Pentecost and Christmas.
Since national, national or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend according to the calendar, it has become a practice to move the working day in cases where we work only one day before or after the holiday.
The price for long weekends is, however, that the previous Saturdays we stay hard and in the round.
The day that immediately precedes or follows the holiday has been regulated for many years by the Minister of Labour in a special decree.
The law applies equally to all employers and the workers employed by them, to public employees and to persons in the public service.
It does not apply to companies and institutions that operate without interruption or, with regard to their purpose, operate even on public holidays.
This year, the change in the working rules will take place only around the end-of-year holidays: from 24 December, life in the country will almost stop, or according to past experience, most people work the days between Christmas and New Year's Eve in advance or use the saved holidays in this way.
Next year, several of our holidays fall in the middle, respectively at the end of the week, also the shifts of the working day will be less than this year.
For the first time, the calendar is transformed around Labor Day, so that workers can stay home for four days afterwards.
Saturday, April 26, will be a working day, so that Friday, May 2, can be a day of rest.
Dalí's move is related to the holiday of 23 October: Saturday 18 October will be used instead of Friday 24.
The end of the year next year will be able to take place entirely under the sign of holidays, because from December 24 they will have almost nonstop holidays despite the fact that New Year's Eve falls on a Wednesday.
