Banks want to solve the crisis
The US Federal Reserve, the European Central Bank and the central banks of Britain, Switzerland and Canada have decided to fight together against the crisis in the financial markets.
Thus, more than a hundred billion dollars will reach the currency markets through auctions.
In these auctions, banks auction the interest rate at which they are willing to borrow money.
For example, the US Fed will put forty billion dollars to auction, and another twenty-four will be made available to the European and Swiss central banks.
This is the first time since the attacks on the eleventh of September that national central banks have agreed on such a coordinated approach to prevent or reduce the consequences of a financial crisis.
"This move is intended to address the economy's biggest problems, which is the growing lack of free capital that banks can lend," Bernard Baumohl of Economic Outlook Group, a consultancy, wrote in a report to clients.
"Coordinated action by central banks has reduced the likelihood of a recession in the United States from 65 percent to fifty percent," Baumohl added in his report.
Banks have already lost sixty billion dollars to non-performing loans, especially in the United States.
Analysts expect billions more losses.
"Central banks must be really worried about what might happen next now that they have decided to do this," said Kieran Davies, chief economist at ABN Amro.
"It looks like the situation is really bad," he added.
Central banks fear that if banks themselves have difficult access to credit, they will also lend more expensively to their customers.
This would reduce consumption and send the U.S. economy into recession with potential effects on global economic growth.
Central banks made the decision after failing to cut the so-called LIBOR rate, the London interbank rate used to lend money in the interbank market.
This meant that banks were still worried about lending money to each other, even though the central banks of the US, Canada and the UK had cut their interest rates several times during the autumn.
"It will have the same effect as a further decline in interest rates," Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting told Reuters.
Some analysts do not believe that the central banks' move will help stave off the crisis because it does not solve the underlying problem, which is the collapse of the US housing market.
