600,000 people failed to exchange their driver's licenses
Six hundred thousand drivers missed the deadline and did not manage to exchange their old driving licence, which expires at the end of the year.
Today is the last day for people to apply for an exchange so that the authorities can still issue them a new card by the end of the year.
However, the ministry is not afraid that hundreds of thousands of drivers without a valid license will take to the road after the New Year.
According to the authorities, the cards have not been exchanged mainly by those who no longer even want to drive.
While municipalities report a sharp decline in interest in exchanging driving licenses, authorities in the capital are overwhelmed with applications and interest in replacing the license has increased this week.
The municipality takes away around 2,000 clients a day.
There is a queue wait of about half an hour.
In Prague, about 140,000 drivers have not yet exchanged their driving licenses.
It takes twenty days to issue a new card.
However, it is possible to apply for extradition within a shortened period of five days.
In this case, however, the driver will pay five hundred crowns.
Motorists who do not manage to change their licence by the end of the year and go on the road without a valid driving licence will face a fine from January.
The offender pays a maximum of two thousand crowns.
However, a police officer can also solve the offense by agreement.
In the case of an administrative offense, the fine rises to 2500 crowns.
According to previous information, even a person who does not go anywhere could be fined by the town hall.
He reportedly could have paid up to 30,000 crowns.
The ministry has previously called on the authorities to be lenient and impose a fine of no more than one thousand crowns.
According to the spokesman of the Ministry of Transport, Karel Hanzelka, however, there is no threat of tens of thousands of fines.
A driver's license is a document that people can decide whether they want it or not.
It is not an identity card that every person must have valid.
People who no longer want to drive should give up their driving licence.
Just take it away or send it by registered mail to the relevant municipal office.
At the end of the year, licences issued between 1964 and 1993 will cease to be valid.
However, motorists must gradually exchange other types of driving licences.
People with documents from 1994 to 2000 still have three years to exchange.
The licences, which were issued between 2001 and 2004, expire in December 2013.
According to Hanzelka, there are about 2.6 million other documents.
