Other places are also becoming more beautiful, such as Trinidad.
Since tourism brings much-needed money, its development has the green light.
Over the past fifteen years, new hotels have sprung up not only in Havana, but especially in Varadero, on the coast of the province of Holguín and on islands such as Cayo Coco, Cayo Guillermo and others.
Cuba offers one more indulgence, which is unique in the world and will be appreciated especially by trainees.
Cane from large plantations was transported to sugar factories on narrow tracks by steam and motor trains.
Their fleet has not been renewed for many decades, so you can see working machines whose contours are elsewhere only in museums.
Where to go?
The most famous places most visitors to Cuba will not miss.
And so there is no need to write much about Varader or Havana.
Perhaps just to remind that in the already mentioned Hemingway homestead there is a museum and who likes this writer, should not miss a visit.
Viñales Valley One of the most picturesque corners of Cuba is the Viñales Valley in the west of the island.
Lush vegetation grows from the limestone bedrock.
Mogotes, limestone loafs and rocks rise steeply from the valley floor and fertile soil has taken hold in their cavities, making the weathered rocks covered with dense vegetation.
The valley is where perhaps the finest Cuban tobacco is grown.
With its final form you can meet if you visit one of the Havana factories for the production of cigars.
Maybe someone will find it interesting that the Chilean episode of Major Zeman was filmed there.
Trinidad
An ancient city that was founded not long after the Spaniards colonized the island.
The slave and sugar trade brought him fame and fortune.
Wealth was reincarnated in the beauty and grandeur of a small town.
Colonial Spanish architecture, greatly influenced by later French settlers, has hardly changed in four centuries.
Trinidad, between the sea and the Escambray Mountains, is a place so remote that even in the 50s of the last century there was no road that would connect the region with the rest of the country.
That isolation helped him stay away.
Nothing was built there, and therefore nothing was demolished, everyone was glad to have a roof over their heads.
If you have more time for Trinidad than one afternoon, then it is worth visiting the nearby interesting places such as Playa Ancón Beach or the Valley of the Sugar Factories.
In the evening, you should go to Casa de la Música, which comes alive after dark and the music in it is silent in the morning.
Baracoa
The town in the very east of Cuba is considered by some to be the most beautiful on the island.
Surely the journey itself influences such a view.
The two roads leading there from Guantánamo have to cross high and rugged mountains and pass through nature that has hardly been affected by human activity.
The eastern outpost of Cuba has been inscribed by UNESCO on the World Heritage List thanks to its intact nature.
