If it turns out that the situation on the political scene would change, politicians would be willing to save more, it could be postponed to 2010.
But I don't anticipate this change," he said.
Debts are rising
The national debt consists of the debts of the central government and arises mainly from the accumulation of state budget deficits.
The sovereign debt is financed by treasury bills, government bonds, direct loans or, for example, loans from the European Investment Bank.
The state's internal debt has risen by CZK 38.5 billion to CZK 719.4 billion so far this year.
So far this year, the state's external debt has risen by CZK 1.7 billion to CZK 123.3 billion.
The so-called marketable state debt reached CZK 803.3 billion at the end of September and has fallen by CZK 13.7 billion since June.
The average maturity of the state debt increased to 6.5 years.
"Total debt grew by 13 percent year-on-year for the first to third quarters, which is really a lot for how the economy is doing.
Interestingly, the increase is generated mainly for bonds, where the increase is 20 percent.
