Memory load
After more than sixty years in a confidential regime, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which recount the fate of 17.5 million victims of Hitler's regime, are open to the public.
Until then, the 47 million archival documents stored in Bad Arolsen (Hesse) over a length of 27 km had been accessible only for "humanitarian" purposes, that is to say, individually and by name, at the request of the former victim or his or her legitimate persons.
Eleven states in charge of managing the archives - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May to open them to scholars and historians.
As the process of ratification of this agreement by all states is complete, the opening took effect yesterday.
Sensitive information
Free access for historians to Bad Arolsen will make it possible to examine "in particular the movements of prisoners, the population of the camps and the state of health of forced laborers", explains Reto Meistern, director of these archives managed by the Comité international de la Croix-rouge (CICR).
Until recently, several States, including Germany, were opposed to the disclosure of these named documents to the public because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
Such as the presumed homosexuality or mental disability of some victims of deportation.
The registers of concentration camps or arrest warrants compiled by the Gestapo were collected after the war for the practical purpose of finding deported or forced labor civilians, providing them with proof of their internment in order to open the way for their compensation.
Even today, more than 300 permanent employees in Bad Arolsen deal with tens of thousands of individual applications.
However, for part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited benefit.
"Nothing fundamentally new can be expected from these documents," Prof. Wolfgang Benz, director of the Center for the Study of Anti-Semitism at Berlin's Technische Universität, said in 2006.
