Congress approves MiFID transposing effective November 1
In parallel with the parliamentary deliberations that concluded today with a congressional vote on amendments incorporated by the Senate into the bill, the government has subjected a public hearing to an ordinance that develops the new law, with the aim of both entering into force before the end of the year.
Representatives of individual parties unanimously highlighted the efforts of deputies and senators to negotiate and agree on the best standard to guarantee investor protection and detailed regulation of the activities of entities necessary for the effective functioning of markets.
The MiFID Directive, which regulates the Securities Trading Act, envisages the modernisation of financial markets while strengthening investor protection, improving the supervisory powers of the State Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and promoting cooperation between the various supervisory bodies of the European Union.
The new legislation will make it possible to provide financial advisory services to specialised firms as well as natural or legal persons and creates a new type of financial services firm (ESIS), financial advice companies (AFIs) that join securities companies, securities brokerage offices and portfolio management companies.
In addition, the number of venues for the execution of transactions in financial instruments is being extended by connecting MTFs and order internalisation systems to regulated secondary markets to compete with existing stockbrokers.
The law also obliges investment services firms to disseminate information on key aspects of their business profile, risk exposure and risk management methods to the market, and requires a statement of all operations carried out to simplify oversight by the CNMV.
During the Congressional Trade Committee hearings, several amendments were introduced, among which the one stands out to treat securitized claims as a "complex" financial instrument due to the high danger to the investor, which has been demonstrated by what has happened in the US with high-risk mortgage debt (subprime).
Moreover, the transposition of the directive has been used to legally define the functions that bachelors in economics and business management can hold 30 years after a royal decree was passed in 1977 outlining the professional functions reserved for economists.
At the same time, the Senate included the creation of new professions in the financial sector, such as an intermediary that will work externally, will not require permission from the CNMV and will be able to provide services of trading in products and acquiring clients for various investment firms at the same time.
