At the time, the bank managed record deposits worth more than £25 billion, which gradually declined over the course of two and a half months due to customer distrust, even though the government had offered a hundred per cent guarantee for the money and would extend it until the end of the crisis.
Virgin, which will replace the entity with its financial business brand Virgin Money, needs to raise around a quarter of the revenue invested in UK banks over the next three years to raise the remaining £18 billion and reach the £30 billion target.
The group of tycoon Richard Branson, known in the UK for his eye-catching advertising campaigns, plans to spend £50 million (about €70 million) a year on advertising and marketing to achieve its resolution.
Northern Rock this week identified the offer from the Virgin consortium, which makes up three other companies, as the one it would prefer to save them from bankruptcy.
