Fears of a new gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
With a dispute between Russia and Ukraine over natural gas prices, there is an increasing risk that Russian supplies of this fuel to Western Europe may be affected.
Most of the Russian fuel exported to the European Union (EU) is pipeline through Ukraine, and any dispute between the two countries is closely watched.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow raises gas prices for Ukraine, it will charge Russia higher transit fees.
A previous dispute between the two last year reduced supplies to EU states.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow comes as the Ukrainian government and Russia's state-owned gas monopoly, Gazprom, are trying to agree on how much Ukraine will have to pay for Russian gas in 2008.
Gazprom says it will have to charge Ukraine more, having agreed to pay up to 50% more for the gas it obtains from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say this could mean Ukraine will have to pay 40% more for its supplies from Gazprom.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states during the negotiations," Ukrainian Economy Minister Anatoly Kinach told Reuters.
"Changes in gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the level of transit fees [to Western Europe] through Ukraine."
The last major dispute between Moscow and Kiev caused a reduction in supplies from Gazprom to Ukraine in January 2006.
This caused a crushing fall in exports to Western Europe, which sharply increased prices.
Russian gas accounts for one quarter of supplies to the European Union.
Russia has the largest gas reserves in the world, but much of it remains underutilized.
As a result, Gazprom replenishes its own gas supplies from Turkmenistan and other former Soviet Central Asian republics.
NHS 'must control foreign workers'
The Comptroller said the Scottish NHS Chambers needed to improve criminal record checks on non-European staff.
The recommendation from Supreme Audit Office President Robert Black came after a foreign doctor working in Scotland was linked to the June attacks on Glasgow airport.
Mr Black is also concerned that the Scottish NHS does not have a precise idea of the amount of foreign staff it employs.
But his report emphasized that other key checks were carried out in order on a sample of five health authorities.
In the wake of the attacks on Glasgow Airport in June, the President of the Supreme Audit Office took an interest in personnel recruited from outside the European Economic Area.
Twenty-eight-year-old Bilal Abdullah, an Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was detained at the airport after someone drove a Jeep into the door of the main terminal building.
He was one of three doctors who appeared at the Central Criminal Court via video bridge accused of links to bomb attempts in the UK.
NHS chambers are expected to check foreign personnel for qualifications, experience and authorisation to work in the UK prior to their employment.
Although Scotland's health commissions use Disclosure Scotland for criminal background checks, the agency has no authority to obtain such information outside Britain.
The report by the President of the Supreme Audit Office says, among other recommendations, that the commissions should be guided by the guidelines of the Criminal Records Bureau, which helps employers with audits in several countries.
"Although we found that part of the staff records contained evidence of these checks, they are not carried out regularly," the report said.
Mr Black said the NHS Scotland was in line with its own pre-staff clearance policy, but added: "Our report highlights areas where the system could be improved to ensure that accurate information on the amount of foreign staff is available."
BMA Scotland chairman Dr Peter Terry said it was "very unlikely" that pre-staff checks would identify potential NHS staff who could commit a terrorist act in the future.
"The report suggests that the current pre-staff checks in the Scottish NHS are working well and it is unclear what additional value these comments will bring," he said.
Health Authorities Scotland have said they currently have 1,161 foreign workers, the vast majority of whom are doctors and nurses.
However, the president of the Supreme Audit Office pointed out that these numbers are likely to be higher also because the commissions had trouble identifying personnel with residence permits.
The survey also found that established audit procedures at NHS bodies in the areas of Ayrshire and Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire and Lothian are largely carried out.
They included checks on passports, work permits and qualifications.
The Scottish Government is currently revising its pre-staff screening policy and guidelines for NHS foreign workers.
Health Minister Nicola Sturgeon said: "I wanted to do this work immediately after the terrorist attack on Glasgow Airport.
She added that the Scottish Government, in agreement with health commissions, would consider the report's recommendations and ensure best practice appeared in the updated guidelines for pre-staff screening of all staff - including foreign staff - which it plans to issue next month.
Joy Division wins film awards
Control, a biopic about the late Joy Division singer Ian Curtis, won five awards at the British Independent Film Awards, including Best Picture.
Awards were also given to star Sam Riley, who worked in a warehouse until the role of Curtis, director Anton Corbijn and Toby Kebell in a supporting role.
Lady Judi Dench was named Best Actress for the thriller Notes on a Scandal.
And James Bond star Daniel Craig won a Variety award for bringing British cinema to the world stage.
The awards were presented at London's Roundhouse.
Control describes Curtis' path to fame with Joy Division until his suicide in 1980 at the age of 23.
The black-and-white film – whose soundtrack includes The Killers, David Bowie and New Order – cost just £3 million.
But Dutch photographer Corbijn, formerly known for his iconic U2 album cover Joshua Tree, won two awards – Best Director and Best Debuting Director.
Rock music was the focus of another award-winning winner - as Julien Temple's film about Clash singer Joe Strummer won the award for Best Documentary.
The Best Actor badge went to Viggo Mortensen for his role as the driver of a Russian mafia boss in David Croenberg's London thriller Eastern Promises.
Ray Winstone, who has a reputation for playing tough guys, won the Richard Harris Award for outstanding contributions to British cinema.
The fifty-year-old, whose films include Scum, Nil By Mouth and Sexy Beast, is currently filming the next episode of Indiana Jones - Kingdom of the Crystal Skull.
Winstone said he was proud of the award, which is named after the star of the films Camelot and Harry Potter Harris, who died in 2002.
"People like Richard Harris and Albert Finney have opened doors for people like me," he added.
"I was lucky enough to meet Richard Harris a few times.
He's my man, a great actor of his time, I'm very honored."
The independent film awards, known as Bifs, are awarded by a jury of filmmakers, actors and festival organizers.
Bif advocates and patrons include Mike Figgis, Ken Loach, Ewan McGregor, Samantha Morton, Bill Nighy, Meera Syal and Michael Winterbottom.
Saudi Arabia arrests 208 people for terror plot
Saudi Arabia announced yesterday that it had arrested 208 militants for being members of cells preparing an imminent attack on an oil facility, as well as spiritual and security forces.
State television said the world's largest oil exporter said one of the cells wanted to smuggle missiles into the country.
Al-Qaeda sympathizers have campaigned against the monarchy, an ally of the United States, since the invasion of Iraq in 2003.
A television report reported that a cell of eight militants led by a foreigner was planning an attack on an oil facility in Ash-Sharqiyah province.
Saudi Arabia is building a 35,000-strong rapid reaction force to defend the facility since al-Qaeda's failed attack on the world's largest oil processing plant in Abqaiq in 2006.
The report quoted an internal statement from the ministry as saying that 18 of those arrested belonged to a cell headed by a "rocket launch expert" who had slipped into the country.
She said the militants planned to smuggle eight missiles into the kingdom.
22 detainees were supposed to be preparing the murder of clerics and security personnel.
The government urged clerics to do more to prevent Saudis from going to Iraq to join al-Qaeda militants fighting allied troops and a U.S.-backed Shiite government that conservative Sunni Saudis consider heretical.
Al-Qaeda militants believe the authorities have co-opted many clerics in Saudi Arabia to support the royal family that controls the government.
The militants — backed by calls by al-Qaeda leader Saud Osama bin Laden to target the pro-Western Saudi government — targeted foreign apartment complexes, government buildings and energy facilities.
"This war was a huge effort by the security forces in the past... five months," an internal ministry spokesman told state television.
A 16-member "media cell" in Medina was also arrested to promote "Takfiri thinking" — the ideology of Sunni Muslim radicals that encourages violence against Muslims labeled as infidels and apostates.
Among those arrested were 32 people accused of providing financial support to militants.
The climate on Venus may be a glimpse into Earth's future
Scientists announced yesterday that Venus may once have been a pleasant place to live.
Data from an orbiting European station show that the planet is even more like Earth's headstrong twin than previously thought.
Venus is Earth's closest planetary neighbor.
The two worlds are roughly the same size and follow similar orbits, but Venus is slightly closer to the Sun.
Scientists now believe that billions of years ago, conditions on Venus were similar to those on Earth and may have been habitable.
But the runaway greenhouse effect caused by carbon dioxide, atmospheric erosion by solar radiation, and a lower rotational speed have sent Venus down a completely different path of evolution.
Today, the planet is waterless, the surface temperature is hot enough to melt lead, and devastated by hurricane-force storms and winds.
Findings from the European Space Agency's Venus Express spacecraft, which studied the planet for a year, offer a modest glimpse of how Earth might evolve in the event of catastrophic climate change.
Professor Fred Taylor, from the University of Oxford's Department of Physics and one of the leaders of the Venus Express mission, said: "It is becoming increasingly clear why the climate on Venus is so different from that on Earth, even though the planets themselves are otherwise quite similar.
"Our new data make it possible to construct a scenario in which Venus, like Earth, possibly with a habitable environment, began billions of years ago."
