Still wide open
Mitt Romney said it was not dignified for presidential candidates to answer questions from a snowman.
Despite this, the Republican presidential candidates eventually agreed to a YouTube debate in which ordinary voters recorded their questions on video and forwarded them to the candidates for broadcast.
None of the questions aired on Wednesday, November 28, were as comical as the snowman who asked Democrats about global warming in a second-party debate on YouTube.
But the questions and answers this time reflected much about the state of the Republican Party heading into next year's election.
It's unclear exactly how producers from CNN, one of the sponsors of the debate, selected the clips to be shown to aspiring candidates.
But the first half hour of the debate, the longest time devoted to a single topic, was focused on immigration.
This issue is one of the strongest Republican themes.
CNN asked a panel of undecided voters to turn the wheel when they heard something gratifying: the announcer saw peaks of approval as candidates talked about a tough approach at the border.
The hardest and longest exchange took place between Rudy Giuliani, the nation's leading candidate, and Mr. Romney, who scrambled ahead in key early votes in Iowa and New Hampshire.
Mr. Giuliani is trying to shake off the reputation of a man who, as mayor of New York, was soft on illegal immigrants.
He attacked Mr. Romney, accusing the former governor of Massachusetts of hiring illegal immigrants to work on his home.
The two struggled particularly fiercely, when questioners asked if either candidate would support "amnesty" (giving illegal immigrants normal status and citizenship).
Supporting candidates like Duncan Hunter, a California congressman, and Tom Tancredo, a congressman from Colorado, have managed to throw their bit into the mill.
Neither of the two has a chance of being nominated, but both remain in the game, perhaps because they have sounded the immigration alarm earlier and harder than the others.
On immigration, at least, the candidates have roughly the same view: more strictness at the border, no tolerance for illegal migrants.
This issue, along with concerns about toxic toys from China and other concerns about the outside world, helps Republicans forget or minimize the rift between libertines and Christian conservatives.
But the debate became very uncomfortable when it came to other topics.
Mr Giuliani was asked why he had supported the possession of firearms in the past.
John McCain and Mr. Romney debated whether the simulated heating technique should be considered torture.
One interviewer asked if the candidates believed every word in the Bible.
Mr. Giuliani stumbled through to the conclusion that even though the Bible was his favorite book, he probably didn't believe literally the story of Jonah and the whale.
Another questioner asked if Jesus would support the death penalty.
Mike Huckabee — who is now against all odds in first place in a recent survey in Iowa thanks to his longtime Christian conservatism — said the death penalty is unpleasant but necessary.
Pressed to decide whether Jesus would agree, he said that Jesus was too smart to run, earning him laughter.
The duel remains extremely open.
Mr. Huckabee's surge in Iowa coincides with recent fundraising successes and Ron Paul's loud cheerfulness at Wednesday's debate.
The two have bounced back as both wings of the party still can't agree on more familiar and traditional candidates.
In 1980 and 2000, one of the candidates united the party very early and convincingly with a winning message of American greatness on his lips, winking at both wings of the party.
This time, the party is divided, and the outcome is far from clear-cut.
Labour's Pain
Gordon Brown again found a trap into which he could fall; His way out remains the same.
While this is customary for British political scandals, this one is not particularly spicy.
No orders seem to have been sold, no bills in a Parisian hotel have been mysteriously paid, no extramarital fingers have been sucked.
But the barricaded Gordon Brown could do without discovering that some wealthy businessman had masked £650,000 ($1.3 million) in contributions to the ruling Labour Party under the names of other people for four years, and that the party had failed to report it.
Two months ago, when the prime minister avoided calling an election and insulted the British intelligentsia by claiming that the decision was not influenced by the polls, there was hope that he would ensure a resilient and effective government.
Instead, as the increasingly witty deputy leader of the Liberal Democrats put it, the once-feared Mr. Brown has changed from Stalin to Mr. Bean.
The clumsy rescue of troubled Northern Rock bank showed weaknesses in management and poor judgment under fire.
Ill-conceived proposals to change the tax code have united companies against the government.
The loss of personal data for 25 million people has exposed unimaginable administrative bungling.
A trio of retired generals started a mutiny in the House of Lords; They protested against cuts in military spending, arguing that being commander of the armed forces was a part-time job.
Now there are multi-edged gifts from David Abrahams; Peter Watt, Labour's general secretary (and former guardian of internal discipline), has already resigned.
None of this means that Mr. Brown is inevitably heading for his end.
Despite this, governments can reach a tipping point beyond which they find governing difficult.
The people don't trust politicians and don't like them, but they usually push aside their distrust when a new bunch takes over.
When it seems clear that a prime minister is unlikely to improve anything, and may not even be in office for long, the relegation is gone: the civil service becomes leaky, ministers start briefing, the press looks for bad news, and the government becomes distracted and defensive.
In one respect, Mr Brown's position is particularly difficult because, unlike other political leaders, he cannot assume the position of a new broomstick.
As much as he would like to distance himself from Tony Blair, he was his first officer.
For example, the problems with Northern Rock and the IRS records are linked to the decisions Mr Brown made as Chancellor of the Exchequer.
And even if he wasn't directly involved in Blairite troubles, such as a lengthy investigation into party financing caused by "ranks for money," voters may well conclude that he was.
Yet Mr. Brown's troubles are not as bad as they seem.
The blunders are not as horrific as conservatives make them.
As for Mr. Bean, no one has died or been downright deceived.
And the cure, painful as it may be, is to provide what Mr. Brown's Stalinist tendencies have always promised: reliable, solid, and slightly brutal government.
The latest fuss about political donations is a good example.
Garboid Mr. Abrahams, who compares his donations to charity, says he didn't want any publicity for his charity.
That may be true, but the decision was not up to him.
The laws against the anonymity of large political donors are clear and exist for a simple reason: the public has a right to know who might be buying access to those who govern the country.
Mr Watt, who said that he knew of Mr Abrahams' procedure but did not know that it was illegal, will certainly be questioned thoroughly; so did Jon Mendlesohn, Labour's main fundraiser, who learned of the tricky donations in October.
But so far, Mr. Brown is not involved; There is nothing to suggest that he knew about these plots, although the bulk of the payments were made after he took office in June.
So far, the Prime Minister has done half the work.
He was very quick to condemn this violation of the law by his own party, but he diluted his resolve by resorting to a tried-and-true instrument, a commission to investigate the matter—headed by a retired bishop and judge.
In this case, the lessons are not complicated.
If the law has been broken, it is a matter for the police.
In addition, there are other things that Mr Brown needs to do, such as finding a permanent chairman of the independent Committee on Standards in Public Life, which has had none for six months, and moving forward with real reform of party funding.
That would require Labour, which is in dire straits, to cooperate with the Conservatives and perhaps even give up their special financial relationship with the unions - a bitter pill for a stalwart party member like Mr Brown.
But he should face a few simple facts.
The Conservatives now have a decent lead in the polls; He has two years to win back voters; And the only way to win is unassailable integrity and high competence.
Card sharks
Is the subprime crisis affecting the US credit card market?
When there is blood in the water, the dorsal fins naturally begin to flicker excitedly.
Now that America's housing market is languishing, predators have targeted the credit card market there.
Analysts at Goldman Sachs say credit card losses could reach $99 billion if other consumer credit options were infected from subprime mortgages.
Signs of tension are clear.
The number of cases of inability to repay (with a delay of more than 30 days in payment) and debited accounts (accounts that the provider considers unenforceable) is increasing.
HSBC said last month it had lost $1.4 billion in the U.S. consumer credit market — also due to insolvent credit card loans.
But it is too early to panic.
Bills written off and inability to repay are still few.
According to Moody's, the 3.89% insolvency rate in the third quarter was almost a full percentage point below average.
The deteriorating rates can partly be explained by technical reasons.
A change in the U.S. personal bankruptcy laws of 2005 has led to a sharp decline in the number of reported bankruptcies, which account for a large portion of credit card losses; Thus, the number of reports (and thus the number of write-offs) would increase regardless of whether the general conditions for borrowers deteriorated.
The industry also shows a good maturity rate, which shows how much consumers repay monthly on their debt.
And confidence in securities secured by credit cards is solid, despite paralysis in other corners of structured finance.
Dennis Moroney of research firm TowerGroup predicts that their emissions for 2007 will be 25% higher than last year.
There are certainly direct paths for contagion between the sub-prime crisis and the credit-card market: when equity loans dry up, consumers are more likely to take on credit card debt.
But credit card issuers look more at cash flow than the value of collateral, so falling home prices do not necessarily mean a change in borrowers' trustworthiness.
They can even be beneficial for lenders.
Consumers' incentive to repay their mortgages decreases when the value of their property falls below the value of the loan; As a result, the debt on the cards moves up the list of priorities to repay.
Card issuers can also respond more quickly and flexibly to more turbulent conditions than mortgage lenders by changing interest rates or debt limits.
In theory, this should reduce the risks of rapid changes in the prices of guarantee items.
"It's not going to happen that we just rethink all the loans one fine morning," says Gary Perlin, chief financial officer at Capital One.
While the risk of a sub-prime mortgage-style explosion is low, the danger of gradual weakening is far more real.
If lower home prices and debt reduction push America into recession, the credit card industry faces a darker future.
Watch out for those dorsal fins.
British bankers plead guilty in Enron case
Three British bankers who were due to be tried for their roles in fraud linked to former Enron financial executive Andrew Fastow changed their testimony on Wednesday and pleaded guilty.
David Bermingham, Giles Darby and Gary Mulgrew initially denied guilt in seven fraud charges in which he and Fastow were alleged to have participated in financial fraud in 2000 -- to enrich themselves at the expense of their employers.
They were due to appear in court in January.
But during the trial before U.S. District Judge Ewing Werlein Jr., each pleaded guilty to one fraud.
The case of the three former executives of Greenwich NatWest, a unit of Royal Bank of Scotland Group PLC, made headlines throughout the two years of extradition proceedings.
In the United States, their case is one of the pending parts of an investigation launched after the collapse of Enron in 2001.
The allegations against them in 2002 alerted Mr. Fastow that he was the target of a government investigation into the collapse of Enron.
The indictment against the bankers -- who have earned the nickname "NatWest Three" -- alleges that they came to Houston in 2000 to plot a fraud with Fastow and his former senior aide, Michael Kopper.
Greenwich NatWest invested in a partner subsidiary of Enron controlled by Fastow, who was the architect of a host of Enron's scams that pushed Enron in a spiral toward bankruptcy.
At the beginning of 2002, the bank valued its stake in this branch at zero, but our three Britons knew that it was in fact worth considerably.
The company, under Kopper's control, bought the bank's stake in the branch for $1 million.
The bankers in question paid Kopper $250,000 for a stake in the company.
According to the indictment, Fastow falsely informed Enron that the energy company would pay $20 million for its stake in Greenwich NatWest.
But the $20 million actually went to the British bankers, Fastow and others.
The bankers received $7.3 million, according to the indictment, and Fastow, Kopper and others received about $12.3 million.
In January 2004, Fastow pleaded guilty to two counts of conspiracy for his role in the collapse of Enron.
The British trio were arrested three months later.
Fastow is currently serving a six-year sentence at a federal prison in Louisiana.
Kopper is serving a three-year and one-month sentence at a facility in Texarkana.
All three Britons were at large on $1 million bail, which ordered them to remain in the United States for an upcoming trial.
Enron, once the country's seventh-largest company, collapsed in December 2001 after years of accounting trickery made it impossible to hide billions in debt or report failed speculation as profitable.
The collapse has cut thousands of jobs, more than $60 billion in market value, and more than $2 billion in retirement.
Enron founder Kenneth Lay and former chief executive Jeffrey Skilling were convicted last year for their roles in the company's downfall.
Skilling is serving more than twenty-four years in prison.
Lay's convictions for conspiracy, fraud and other charges were swept away after he died of heart disease last year.
Moscow's Non-Helplessness
The price of the Gulfstream G550, equipped with a Rolls-Royce engine and enough fuel for a nonstop flight from Moscow to Los Angeles, starts at $54 million.
For some of Russia's wealthy, however, they are pennies to return.
"It can carry up to 18 passengers," says Dan Firer, a representative of Gulfstream.
"But none of them are interested in that many jobs because it's for a close family or a corporate president."
Mr. Firer sat in a Gulfstream booth last Friday at the Millionaires Show, a four-day of conspicuous consumerism at a mammoth exhibition center on the outskirts of the capital.
In addition to Gulfstream, more than 200 other luxury suppliers set up their stands, hoping to lure newly wealthy Russians with everything from mahogany-inlaid yachts to diamond-decorated car bulkheads they wouldn't be ashamed of for 50 cents.
Mr. Firer looked cautiously at the bright orange Porsche in the next stall.
"That's a nice car, but against us it's dimes and dimes," he said.
"After the United States, Russia is the second largest private jet market."
On the waves of oil, money is pouring into the Russian capital just as much as when Dallas had its days.
"We went through the same stage in the '80s when some Americans got enormously rich and went to Europe, where they were seen as materialists," said Marshall Goldman, a fourth-year student at Harvard's Davis Center for Russian and Eurasian Studies.
Like the Saudi spendthrifters of the '70s and the Japanese of the '90s, the Russians are becoming the world's most prominent spenders.
The most exclusive luxury brands are looking for their share in this Klondike.
Elsewhere in Moscow this week, a luxury industry conference brought in Donatella Versace, Tom Ford and Bernard Arnault, chairman of the LVMH Group, to exchange ideas on how to sell expensive goods in markets like Russia's.
(The conference is hosted by The International Herald Tribune, owned by The New York Times Company.)
Russia has 53 billionaires with a total fortune of $282 billion, according to Forbes magazine's list of the richest people.
In addition, the local main institute in the field Center for Economic and Financial Research has published a report on the development of personal wealth in the former Soviet Union, according to which there are 103,000 "second-rate" millionaires in Russia, whose combined fortune is $ 670 billion.
(The World Bank reports that in 2005, 15.8% of Russians lived below the subsistence level.)
"There are hundreds of millionaires in Moscow -- and that's why we're all here," said Nicole Marais, sales and marketing representative at London-based jewellery store David Morris.
She was at the fair for the first time, together with the Russian distributor of this brand, Soho Jewelry Group.
"All the women are impeccably groomed, and the men are each for a fortune."
As they walked through the halls in evening dresses on Sunday evening, twenty-one-year-old Evgenia Yumatova and Svetlana Turovtsova, five years her senior, branded themselves and their clients millionaires.
"I've been looking at the cars and I can't decide between Infiniti, Mercedes and Porsche," said Miss Yumatova, who dressed in designer clothes like a red carpet veteran that makes Joan Rivers look like a housewife.
The fair seemed to be aimed primarily at the nouveau riche, brand-driven Russian buyers who are willing to sit for a few hours in traffic to stroll around a warehouse that garishly mixes Cadillac Escalade, platinum fish, Mövenpick ice cream, custom-made billiard tables, Dubai apartments, Gund stuffed animals and draughts.
Members of the general public could buy tickets for 30 euros ($44.57).
"Russians are interested in which brand is the most expensive and the best," said Mr. Gijrath, who patriotically occupied the booth of Dutch porcelain manufacturer Royal Delft before reproducing Rembrandt's larger-than-life painting from hand-painted blue tiles.
"Of course, the Russians are more interested in glitter."
Indeed, the vendors here say that Russians with old money (10 to 15 years old by Russian standards) have moved from shiny logos to little-known limited-edition brands that would never show up at a shopping fair.
Even so, several thousand people, whether millionaires, millionaires' ambassadors or simple tourists, flooded the exhibition halls every day.
And some of them were buying.
On the first day of the show, last Thursday, Roman Ershov, the local general manager of King Koil beds, said he had sold two mattress sets of silk, cashmere and cotton, interwoven with gold threads, for $70,000 each.
Also on the first day, Mikhail Lyubimov, sales manager of A1 Moto, a company that equips high-end cars with high-end alarms, said his company had sold a bright orange Porsche for $170,000 to a Russian millionaire.
On Sunday afternoon, Andrei Karapetian, president of L.A. Connection, a custom-made luxury car company, said he had sold three car grilles in the style of interconnected chain bracelets for Rolls-Royce Phantoms for $55,000 each.
He showed the reporter the wheel of a car designed for a Russian casino owner that had a string coated with Swarovski crystals so that it looked like roulette.
Price: $22,000 for four such.
"That Russian millionaire who wants ostrich-skin bikes or a portrait of his wife made of cubic zirconium doesn't have to ride those bikes yet," Mr. Karapetian said.
"He stores them in his garage of thirty to forty cars."
Although many of his Russian clients are wealthy, Mr. Karapetian said the phrase "Russian millionaire" doesn't mean anything exclusive these days, given the big rise in property prices here.
"If you bought an apartment in Moscow three or four years ago, you're probably already a millionaire, at least on paper, if not in cash," he said.
"There are more than you think."
Those who are not millionaires could at least pretend to be wealthy at a booth run by Alliance Continental, a Russian asset management firm.
The company erected four red British-style phone booths stuffed with columns of fake million-dollar banknotes.
Azad Karryev, the company's marketing manager, said his team printed 500,000 fake banknotes for the Millionaires Fair.
Passersby stopped to throw around piles of money, or to be photographed by friends on their cell phones relaxing in the midst of substitute wealth, or simply to stuff their pockets with a few million.
"You know, in Moscow everyone can feel like a millionaire," Mr. Karryev said.
Death in New Jersey possibly caused by a spoiled operation
It was the day before Thanksgiving when Roland Livingston looked out of the large windows of the local A Slightly Healthier restaurant and watched the ambulance pull up to a white New England house two houses down West Scott Avenue.
Soon a police patrol car joined.
And then another.
"Then I saw the forensic doctor's van arrive," said Mr. Livingston, the restaurant inspector.
"At that moment, I knew someone had died."
Authorities learned that the dead woman was Olga Arroya, 41, an executive assistant to the director of the Newark Police Department.
