Hope that the Fed will cut interest rates leads to a strengthening of world stock markets
Stock prices on both sides of the Atlantic jumped yesterday after market hopes that the Federal Reserve would try to ease lending conditions by further interest rate cuts were boosted by reassuring remarks from the US Federal Reserve vice-chairman.
Stocks jumped in London, New York and across Europe after Donald Kohn, second only to Ben Bernanke, the Fed's chairman, said executives needed to be "flexible and pragmatic" in responding to ongoing pressure in financial markets.
In an apparent effort to calm irritated markets amid signs of revived credit strain, Mr Kohn said the recent turmoil "partly reversed some improvements in market functioning in late September and October."
He said that if increased volatility persists, the possibility that financial conditions of households and firms will deteriorate further will increase.
Investors see these statements as a signal that the Fed is ready to inject more fresh doses of capital into U.S. markets, and possibly further interest rate cuts to stabilize credit conditions.
The remarks also helped calm Wall Street amid more bad news about the U.S. economy, with apartment sales posting record lows in October.
The consequences of the financial turmoil were underscored by the announcement by investment bank Bear Stearns that it would cut 650 jobs, or 4% of its global workforce, as part of cost-cutting to compensate for heavy losses caused by a failed bet on sub-prime home loans in America.
Only 20 of those jobs are expected to be closed in London, where the bank employs 1,500 people.
In New York, the Dow Jones Industrial Average rose 331 points, or 2.55 percent, to close at 13,289.40, while the better-used S&P 500 rose 2.65 percent.
London's FTSE 100 rose 165.5 points, or 2.7 percent, to close at 6,306.2, with the value of British blue-chips rising by more than £39 billion.
Germany's Dax index rose 2.6 percent and France's CAC40 rose 2.3 percent.
Some time ago, credit tensions in the markets were in full force when, in an auction of the European Central Bank's three-month money packages, these funds were lent to European commercial banks at a rate of 4.7%, the highest since April 2001.
Pressure on the Bank of England to follow the Fed and ECB and dump extra money on London's money markets has increased, with rates on Britain's three-month "Libor" interbank loans rising to their highest since late September of 6.59 percent after an uninterrupted rise since November 12.
England must decide: Owais Shah or Ravi Bopara?
We have two dilemmas, one almost as difficult as the other.
Who will be the number six at bat for England this weekend in Kandy, Owais Shah or Ravi Bopara?
And, in a broader context, no less relevant than the first Test against Sri Lanka, who is to make that decision?
The second question is relevant because David Graveney, chairman of the selection committee, who is at best in borrowed time, is supposed to help Peter Moores, the head coach, and Michael Vaughan, the captain, with the decision, and because the table of Hugh Morris, the England team's chief manager, is starting to fill up with applications for the post of national collector, though not necessarily full-time.
Whoever is not put in sixth place at bat will be unhappy, but life is often not fair, and sport certainly is not.
It is not easy to find what will get one to the top of his profession, while someone else will never get through a lower level, sometimes due to lack of luck rather than ability.
Not only in cricket is the selection challenging and requires a judgement, which in the end must always be subjective.
Is it the right time for Bopara to move up?
Is that fair to Shah, isn't it?
We could ask the same question in another area, let's say here: John Edwards or "Tubby" Banerjee, both smart young executives with a good education and insight into the field, should be promoted to the commission - there is only a place for one.
Who's to say which level is right for a cricketer if he doesn't have a chance to drop or swim to the next one?
Naturally, numbers have a big impact on decision-making, but so do opportunities.
In a team, the cricketer must catch the captain's gaze at the right time if he should take the wicket, and the batter needs regular chances in the starting positions if he is ever to make an impression as a day cricketer.
Capturing the collector's gaze is more complicated.
Last season, for example, there were many better than James Anderson, whose place in the first Test seems assured, even if Stephen Harmison declared himself healthy and pitched like an artilleryman.
Anderson took 32 wickets in first class with 33 runs each.
Chris Tremlett took just 29 at an equally meager average, but both had their moments at the highest level and are hoping for more.
Whether he will play at the Asgiriya Shah or Bopar Stadium may only be a matter of opinion.
The choice can start or finish the careers of both, or it may not have a big impact.
Four years ago in Sri Lanka, Gareth Batty played in every Test and performed well in first class, five wickets and 40 allowed runs, but it was Paul Collingwood, who was fighting for his place at the same time, who eventually became a stable Test Cricketer, who is extra, despite scoring twice a hundred points in Australia against Australia,  perhaps still underestimated.
It is more likely that Graveney, Vaughan and Moores, after one more discussion following today's practice at Asirgiya Stadium, will follow their conservative instincts and prefer Shah's greater experience to Bopar's youthful exuberance.
There are arguments for both.
For Shah, his sparkling and valuable 88-point test innings in Mumbai and 32 first-class innings speak for Shah, compared to six Bopar, who, at twenty-two, is seven years younger and has excellent stats against spin pitching.
But Shah made just ten runs in two innings in May against the Caribbean at the Lord's Test, his home ground in Middlesex, and that, along with the immediate rejection of the collectors when Vaughan wanted to re-fill him for the next game, his batting seemed to take away some of the momentum that was so evident in Mumbai.
The Essex universal, on the other hand, has a joie de vivre in his bones.
Nothing scares him on the cricket pitch and his behaviour off the pitch is symbolised by a recently overturned four-wheel drive car on the exhibition day of the English team's car sponsor, Volkswagen.
He escaped with minor injuries and probably shock, but the first thing he did was pull out his Vodafone (also sponsored, of course) and call Alastair Cook, his teammate who was watching from a distance, to ask him excitedly, "Did you see that?"
Bopara is definitely better in the field, delivering his medium-speed shear pitches on the pitches here that seem to suit him, efficiently and batting with confidence and skill.
Choosing the right person is one thing, choosing the right time is another.
Perhaps this is the real art of selection.
Personally, I'm leaning towards Bopara getting his chance now, which is not to say that Shah won't excel if, as the Ceylon tea leaves suggest, he's the one playing here next weekend.
Buses bring refugees back to work - and to fight al-Qaeda
The first buses full of Iraqi refugees from Syria began arriving in Baghdad yesterday, emptying refugees who had run out of money or expired visas, and others who had hoped the city was returning to normal life.
Some even returned to fight the militants who had driven them from their homes.
Mansoor's bus station was already full of refugees from Syria and Jordan who had returned by private transport before 800 people arrived from Damascus in an official government convoy.
"I decided to go to Syria after they killed many doctors in Baghdad," said Sabah al-Kubaysi, a Sunni doctor.
"I came back today because of what I saw on TV and what I read about in the newspapers, because of what happened in Baghdad and how safe it is now.
"They say the Mahdi army has stopped killing people," he said, referring to the Shiite militia of militant cleric Moqtada al-Sadr, who has temporarily ordered his people to stop fighting.
Qassem al-Atwani, a thirty-eight-year-old Shiite teacher from the predominantly Sunni region of Amariya, returned with his two children because he could not renew his Syrian visas and because the regime there did not allow Iraqis to work.
His Shiite neighbors in Amariya called him to say that local militias, with the support of the U.S. military, had helped push al-Qaeda out of their positions in the west of the capital, and urged him to return.
One of the new arrivals from Jordan is the leader of a Sunni and Shiite tribe driven from his home in Sleikh in northern Baghdad by a grenade attack after urging his fellow citizens to rise up against al-Qaeda.
He returned to fight.
"The day before yesterday, some friends called me and told me that they were starting an anti-Qaeda militia in Sleikh and that they needed me and the support of my boys.
That's why I came back today," said Sabaah Alu Obeidi.
Many spoke of the appeal of appeasement in the capital after the buildup of the U.S. military presence and the growth of local "groups of interested citizens" who are taking arms alongside the U.S. military to defend their neighborhoods.
But more was said to have been driven to return by visa obstruction and money cuts in Damascus, where more than 1.3 million Iraqis have fled in recent years.
Salaam al-Samarraj, a fifty-one-year-old father of three, voiced suspicions shared among refugees that Nouri al-Maliki, the Shiite prime minister, had asked the Syrian government to impose visa restrictions on refugees to force them to return.
According to available data, more than two and a half million people have fled Iraqi sectarian murderers.
"Everything was fine until al-Maliki visited Syria and pressed the government to stop giving Iraqis visas so they would have to go back to Iraq," the Sunni pensioner said.
"I can't trust a government that supports the criminals who burned down my house after I left."
Part of the reason for the reduction in violence is that Sunnis have been pushed out of Shia areas and vice versa, which is reducing tensions in many places.
There are fears that the sudden influx of refugees will rekindle sectarian tensions and lead to another struggle.
Tiny Saarland, good education
Germany's smallest federal state plays a leading role in vocational education, excelling even with the international focus of its universities.
In only one area of education, the Saarland is as concerned about the lack of shortages as the rest of Germany.
"Yesterday I explained to a person who does not come from the Saarland for the fiftieth time that we are no French" - this self-deprecating slogan appears on posters in the Saarland on the occasion of the 50th anniversary of the birthday of this smallest federal state.
At the same time, France and Luxembourg play a major role in the Saarland education system, which ranks fifth in the Cologne Institute for Economic Research (IW) education monitoring.
Traditionally, universities cooperate closely with neighbouring countries.
The University of Saarbrücken was founded by the French in 1948.
To this day, students can finish their studies with a double or even triple diploma.
This corresponds to a reasonably high share of foreign students, which is 15.6%.
After all, an above-average number of Saarland children are admitted to college - many of them without attending grammar school.
"In Saarland, a vocational education system is used," says Axel Plünnecke, IW's education expert.
With more than one in five young people eligible to study at a vocational school, Saarland is more than 7% above the German average.
Compared to the rest of Germany, Saarland offers ample opportunities to combine practical and academic education.
The possibilities to study two subjects are the second best in Germany in terms of population.
Despite practice-oriented education and rising demand, the number of engineering graduates has dropped by a third in recent years.
That is why the Saarland Ministry of Education has now ordered universities to create a promotional campaign for engineering disciplines.
"After the first Pisa study, we have implemented several reforms in general education schools," says a spokesperson for the Ministry of Education.
The government has therefore introduced comparative tests throughout Germany.
In order for children to start learning as early as possible, the last year of nursery school is free of charge - a model that is also being adopted by other federal states.
Whether pupils' results will improve significantly will only be revealed in future comparative studies.
In the 2003 Pisa study, the proportion of at-risk pupils had fallen from 29 to 20 %.
Overall, however, the Saarland has not improved as much as other Länder.
Bavarians are better at counting.
And to Saarland's disappointment, Pisa studies do not compare foreign language skills - otherwise Saarland could score points in this area.
