Venus is the hellish twin of Earth
Despite its life-hostile atmosphere, Venus is more Earth-like than previously thought. Europe's Venus Express spacecraft on Venus has recorded phenomena that occur on Earth in winter: lightning in the atmosphere and wind vortices at the poles.
For nearly three decades, scientists have suspected that Venus is lightning.
Now the European probe Venus Express has produced proof - it has picked up electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere. Lightning flies from cloud to cloud on Venus at an altitude of about 56 kilometers, writes Christopher Russell of the University of California, Los Angeles, in the scientific journal Nature.
According to the well-known theory of the origin of primordial matter, life could have arisen on Earth thanks to lightning. Storms supposedly triggered reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, the cornerstones of life.
That wasn't the case on Venus: "If life ever existed there, it must have been a long time ago," explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, anything alive would hardly be found on the surface of Venus. The atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, and sometimes temperatures are around 500 degrees Celsius.
"Venus may be Earth's hellish twin, but it's a twin," Russell said.
Why Venus, which is so similar to Earth in mass and size, began to evolve completely differently is a fundamental question for ESA's mission.
Since no probe has been sent since the early 90s solely to study Venus, the launch of Venus Express in November 2005 was a milestone in the exploration of this planet.
According to scientists, the latest results of the research, which were presented in several articles in the journal Nature, did not only emphasize the uniqueness of Venus in the solar system.
"They also showed that our neighboring planet is more similar to Earth than previously thought," Esa said.
In addition to the already known wind vortices at the North Pole, scientists have found a cloud vortex at the South Pole that spins significantly faster.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of air currents in Earth's northern hemisphere, writes a research team led by Guiseppe Piccioni of Italy's Instituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second innermost planet in our solar system is almost the same mass as Earth, and with a diameter of 12,100 km, it is almost the same size.
This planet, known as the Morning Star or Evening Star, orbits the Sun in nearly 225 days.
However, it rotates much more slowly around its own axis. One day on Venus lasts 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus with a surface temperature of 460 °C and a pressure of 92 bar(short for bar?) It does not resemble Earth, scientists assume that the two planets formed under very similar conditions.
Water accumulated on both of them. On Earth, however, it remained in the oceans, while from Venus it evaporated into space.
While carbon dioxide on Earth is bound in carbonates, on Venus it makes up most of the atmosphere.
