These are not Warhol's boxes
Anyone who connects Sweden and wooden boxes is not thinking of Andy Warhol, but of Ikea.
Or is it?
Wooden boxes currently produced in Sweden cast dark shadows on the list of Warhol's work.
Most of his listed ninety-four Stockholm brillo boxes are fakes.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" a few months ago expressed doubts about the authenticity of Warhol's 1968 "Brillo Boxes", internal research by the Moderna Museet in Stockholm has produced a disappointing result; The six "Brillo boxes" donated to the Moderna Museet in 1995 by its former director, Pontus Hultén, are copies – as are most of the other Stockholm-type Brillo boxes in circulation on the international art market.
Previous events are a tangled, confusing chain of artistic and curatorial events.
Warhol made his first Brillo boxes in New York in 1964, painting wooden boxes that were based on the red-blue-and-white design of paper boxes of Brillo soap powder.
An exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet in 1968 showcased - with Warhol's permission - hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard. These did not come (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but were supplied directly from the Brillo factory.
These were not works of art, but their models, mere exhibition pieces.
Warhol apparently also gave permission in 1968 for several wooden Brillo crates to be made in Sweden, but these are not on display at the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses of that time now speak of fifteen boxes, which at that time rightfully entered art and auction history as authorized originals - "Andy Warhol's Brillo Boxes" marked Type Stockholm.
Some of them were auctioned off for more than $100,000.
The problem now is that the legendary director of the museum, Pontus Hultén, later falsely claimed that in 1968 around a hundred crates were made and displayed in Sweden, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, 105 Hultén crates were made in Malmö for an exhibition in St. Petersburg only in 1990.
By then, Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief conservator of the Moderna Museet, examined in addition to the six Brillo boxes owned by the museum, three Brillo boxes from a Swedish private collection, two of which were made in Sweden in 1968 and painted with oil white paint after their plywood boards were painted with a brush.
On the contrary, the structure of the 1990 copies revealed that the paint was applied without a previous primer by a painter's roll directly to the plywood board - besides, it is acrylic and not oil paint.
"These boxes have not been authorized by the artist and should be removed from Warhol's official Brillo box list," said Lars Nittve, director of the Moderna Museet: "Unless the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board in New York comes to different conclusions, the Moderna Museet will have to classify six crates from its exhibition collections as 'exhibition material - copies.'"
In July, the Authentication Board announced that it would look into the "core allegations" in the soap powder box case.
But the organization has so far remained relentlessly silent.
